com.spazedog.lib.rootfw3.extenders

Class ShellExtender.Shell

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.spazedog.lib.rootfw3.extenders.ShellExtender.Shell
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ExtenderGroup
    Enclosing class:
    ShellExtender

    public static class ShellExtender.Shell
extends java.lang.Object
implements ExtenderGroup
    This class is used to communicate with the shell.
    Note that this implements the ExtenderGroup interface, which means that it does not allow anything outside RootFW to create an instance of it. Use RootFW.shell() to retrieve an instance.

      • buildCommands

        public ShellExtender.Shell buildCommands(java.lang.String... commands)
        This is the same as addCommands(), only this one will auto create multiple attempts for each command using each defined binary in RootFW.Config.BINARY. You can use the prefix %binary to represent where the binary should be injected.
        For an example, if you add the command buildCommands('%binary df -h'), this method will create new String[]{'busybox df -h', 'toolbox df -h', 'df -h'}. This makes it easier to add multiple attempts without having to type in each attempt via addAttempts().
        Parameters:
        commands - A string containing a command with %binary prefix
        Returns:
        This instance

      • buildAttempts

        public ShellExtender.Shell buildAttempts(java.lang.String... commands)
        This is the same as buildCommands(), only this one just produces one command with generated attempts per argument.
        If you add the command buildAttempts('%binary df -h', '%binary df'), this method will create one command with the attempts new String[]{'busybox df -h', 'toolbox df -h', 'df -h', 'busybox df', 'toolbox df', 'df'}.
        Parameters:
        commands - A string containing a command with %binary prefix
        Returns:
        This instance

      • addCommands

        public ShellExtender.Shell addCommands(java.lang.String... commands)
        This is used to add multiple commands to be executed in the shell. Each argument should be a separate command to be executed. Each command output will be merged in the ShellResult.
        If one command fails (Does not return a valid result code), it will stop executing the rest of the commands.
        Parameters:
        commands - A string containing a command
        Returns:
        This instance

      • addAttempts

        public ShellExtender.Shell addAttempts(java.lang.String... commands)
        This is used to add multiple attempt for one command. The different between this and buildAttempts(), is that this one does not auto generate more attempts based on defined binaries.
        Parameters:
        commands - A string containing an attempts
        Returns:
        This instance

      • setResultCodes

        public ShellExtender.Shell setResultCodes(java.lang.Integer... result)
        Whether or not a command was successful or not, depends on the result code returned by the shell. This result code determines the result of ShellResult.wasSuccessfull() and it also controls when to stop executing multiple command attempts.
        By default, 0 is considered successful, but you might need other result codes to be considered successful as well. This method allows you to add more result codes to be considered successful.
        Parameters:
        result - A result code to be considered successful
        Returns:
        This instance

      • reset

        public ShellExtender.Shell reset()
        Whenever you add commands using builtCommands() and addCommands(), or adds more result codes via setResultCodes(), this is all cached until you execute run().
        This method will reset this cache without having to execute run().
        Returns:
        This instance

      • run

        public ShellExtender.ShellResult run()
        This method will execute all of the commands that has been added via addCommands() and builtCommands().
        Returns:
        a new instance of ShellResult with all of the shell output and information like the result code.

      • run

        public ShellExtender.ShellResult run(java.lang.String command)
        This method allows you to directly execute one single command without having to use addCommands() and builtCommands().
        Note that if you have already used addCommands() or builtCommands(), this argument will just be added to the stack. It does not reset anything before executing.
        Parameters:
        command - One single command to be executed in the shell
        Returns:
        a new instance of ShellResult with all of the shell output and information like the result code.
